{"name":"Ugly","permission":{"default":0,"49AXXoPz63AAzPKB":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":{"type":"String","label":"Description","value":"<p>Taking the&nbsp;<em>Ugly</em> Flaw for your pet shows it's particularly ill-favoured in appearance, which may come with penalties in some situations.</p>\n<p>Ugly animals attract negative attention, and related Fellowship Tests might even suffer a &ndash;10 penalty.</p>\n<p>Each <em>Flaw</em> halves the listed price and improves @JournalEntry[Going To Market]{Availability} by one step.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Note: Exotic items do not have their Availability modified by being Flawed &mdash; they are always difficult to find, even shoddy examples.</p>"},"gmdescription":{"type":"String","label":"Description","value":"<p>Many vendors sell flawed items, but&nbsp;pretend they are anything but. A successful Test with any&nbsp;appropriate skill &mdash; such as Evaluate, or Melee for weapons, or&nbsp;Trade for tools &mdash; will spot such underhanded activities.</p>\n<p>NOTE: Normally, both <em>Ugly</em>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<em>Fine</em> can't be applied to a single animal, but I'm sure there are examples of ugly versions of purebred animals, so I'll not make that a hard rule, and leave it to individual circumstances to dictate.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},"rollable":{"value":false,"label":"Rollable","type":"Boolean","rollCharacteristic":"","bonusCharacteristic":"","defaultDifficulty":"challenging"},"specification":{"value":"","type":"String","label":"Specification"},"source":{"type":"String","label":"Source"}},"flags":{},"img":"modules/wfrp4e-core/icons/traits/trait.png","effects":[],"_id":"ANJdgjV5SIJn7Ype"}
{"name":"Trained*","permission":{"default":0,"49AXXoPz63AAzPKB":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":{"type":"String","label":"Description","value":"<p>This trait represents animals that have been trained through the Animal Training Skill. The skills the animal knows is marked in the brackets. Feel free to create your own trained skills.</p>\n<p><strong>Broken</strong>: The animal has been domesticated. Now tame, it gains +[[/r 2d10]] Fel, even if it has the Bestial trait. Further, it can now learn more Trained traits (see below).</p>\n<p><strong>Calm:</strong> The animal gains a bonus of +10 to Tests to ignore panic caused by the Skittish trait for each point it has in Calm. It can have a maximum of WPB rating in this trait.</p>\n<p><strong>Drive</strong>: The animal is trained to pull a coach, cart, plough, buggy, or similar. The animal can pull up to its own body weight for TB hours without needing to make an Endurance Test. The animal can also pull up to twice its body weight for short hauls of TB minutes. The animal's gains a bonus of +1 TB to do this for each point it has in Drive. It can have a maximum of WPB rating in this trait.</p>\n<p><strong>Entertain</strong>: The animal is trained to entertain others. It adds a +10 bonus to appropriate Entertain, Perform, or Play Tests.</p>\n<p><strong>Fetch</strong>: The animal is trained to fetch. This is normal reserved for Dogs and similar.</p>\n<p><strong>Guard</strong>: The animal is trained to stay in one place or prowl around as a guard, granting it the Territorial Trait.</p>\n<p><strong> Home</strong>: The animal is trained to return home if it is released or lost.</p>\n<p><strong>Magic</strong>:&nbsp;The animal is trained to accept a spellcaster as a rider. Without this Trained trait, the animal typically shies from spellcasters.</p>\n<p><strong>Mount</strong>: The animal will accept a rider. Some creatures are especially belligerent, and will not accept a rider without the correct skill. So, to ride a Griﬀon, you need the Ride (Griﬀon) skill.</p>\n<p><strong>Pack:</strong> The animal is trained to carry great weights on its back. It can carry its Strength rating in Encumbrance points upon its back for each point it has in Pack. This limit is doubled for each step in the Size trait to the creature has above Large. It can have a maximum of TB rating in this trait.</p>\n<p><strong>War</strong>:&nbsp;The animal is trained to carry a rider into the hell of war. It can use its Rider&rsquo;s WP instead of its own for all appropriate Tests</p>"},"gmdescription":{"type":"String","label":"Description","value":"<p>This assumes the following updates are applied to the&nbsp;<em>Trained</em>&nbsp;trait from&nbsp;<strong>WFRP</strong>&nbsp;page 342-343. Of note, look to Broken, which was never supposed to imply the&nbsp;<em>Bestial</em>&nbsp;trait was ignored completely.</p>"},"rollable":{"value":false,"label":"Rollable","type":"Boolean","rollCharacteristic":"","bonusCharacteristic":"","defaultDifficulty":"challenging"},"specification":{"value":"Trained Skills","type":"String","label":"Specification"},"source":{"type":"String","label":"Source"}},"flags":{"_sheetTab":"details"},"img":"modules/wfrp4e-core/icons/traits/trait.png","effects":[],"_id":"I7L7UACo7qOuni3l"}
{"name":"Fine","permission":{"default":0,"49AXXoPz63AAzPKB":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":{"type":"String","label":"Description","value":"<p>For animals the <em>Fine</em> Quality represents a pedigree. Mongrels cannot purchase the&nbsp;<em>Fine</em>&nbsp;Quality to represent breeding, but it could be purchased to show a dog with a particularly pretty face or similar.</p>\n<p>If a Player wants to buy any special breed beyond the generic versions, at least 1 instance of <em>Fine</em>&nbsp;should be bought to show it's a purebred animal accessing the special rules.</p>\n<p>For each <em>Fine</em> Quality the animal has, its price is doubled and its @JournalEntry[Going To Market]{Availability}&nbsp;is one step less.</p>\n<p>A typical Telland actually starts at 7GC (the base cost of 3GC 10/&ndash; is doubled because of the&nbsp;<em>Fine</em>&nbsp;Quality).</p>\n<p>The more <em>Fine</em> Qualities purchased, the stronger the bloodline of the animal, and the more impressive it appears. This brings no advantages beyond bragging rights and high returns if the animal is ever sold.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>"},"gmdescription":{"type":"String","label":"Description","value":"<p>NOTE: Insisting special breeds have the Fine quality is not a firm rule, as you may wish to keep costs low at some points; it's more of a guideline that you should most always follow.</p>"},"rollable":{"value":false,"label":"Rollable","type":"Boolean","rollCharacteristic":"","bonusCharacteristic":"","defaultDifficulty":"challenging"},"specification":{"value":"","type":"String","label":"Specification"},"source":{"type":"String","label":"Source"}},"flags":{},"img":"modules/wfrp4e-core/icons/traits/trait.png","effects":[],"_id":"O7XE1eHAzQTzcMCn"}
{"_id":"mmUpRmsHqbWqmBl7","name":"Amble","permission":{"default":0,"49AXXoPz63AAzPKB":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":{"type":"String","label":"Description","value":"<p>The creature has a smooth gait, making it more comfortable to ride over long distances. Add +Amble hours to any length of time a rider can comfortably ride. Further, reduce the Combat Difficulty for&nbsp;<em>Shooting From Horseback</em>&nbsp;by 1 step.*</p>"},"gmdescription":{"type":"String","label":"Description","value":"<p>*<em>House Rules:</em> You can't ride a horse for longer than <strong>TB</strong> hours a day without picking up some <em>Fatigue Conditions</em>, depending upon the results of an<strong> Endurance Test</strong>. Further, <em>Shooting From Horseback</em> is a penalty of at least –20, depending upon the circumstances. Riders with the <em>Trick Riding</em> Talent reduce this difficulty by 1 step.</p>"},"rollable":{"value":false,"label":"Rollable","type":"Boolean","rollCharacteristic":"","bonusCharacteristic":"","defaultDifficulty":"challenging"},"specification":{"value":"","type":"String","label":"Specification"},"source":{"type":"String","label":"Source"}},"flags":{},"img":"modules/wfrp4e-core/icons/traits/trait.png","effects":[]}
{"_id":"nVwhRohiJRJThYnj","name":"Sure-Feet","permission":{"default":0,"49AXXoPz63AAzPKB":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":{"type":"String","label":"Description","value":"<p>The creature can instinctually find its footing, even when it has a rider on its back. The creature automatically passes all Tests concerning uncertain footing caused by such things as screes, rocky trails, heavy undergrowth, and similar.</p>"},"gmdescription":{"type":"String","label":"Description","value":""},"rollable":{"value":false,"label":"Rollable","type":"Boolean","rollCharacteristic":"","bonusCharacteristic":"","defaultDifficulty":"challenging"},"specification":{"value":"","type":"String","label":"Specification"},"source":{"type":"String","label":"Source"}},"flags":{},"img":"modules/wfrp4e-core/icons/traits/trait.png","effects":[]}
{"name":"Swimmer","permission":{"default":0,"49AXXoPz63AAzPKB":3},"type":"trait","data":{"description":{"type":"String","label":"Description","value":"<p>Start with <em>Swim</em> Skill +10</p>"},"gmdescription":{"type":"String","label":"Description","value":null},"rollable":{"value":false,"label":"Rollable","type":"Boolean","rollCharacteristic":"","bonusCharacteristic":"","defaultDifficulty":"challenging"},"specification":{"value":"","type":"String","label":"Specification"},"source":{"type":"String","label":"Source"}},"flags":{},"img":"modules/wfrp4e-core/icons/traits/trait.png","effects":[],"_id":"s0FI6MpTpfVNyk5P"}
